12.1.2 Structure of the Carbonyl Group






The carbonyl carbon atom is sp2-hybridised and forms three sigma (σ) bonds.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "The fourth valence electron of carbon remains in its p-orbital and forms a π-bond with oxygen by overlap with p-orbital of an oxygen.", "fibs": ["valence"]}
{"text": "In addition, the oxygen atom also has two non bonding electron pairs.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "Thus, the carbonyl carbon and the three atoms attached to it lie in the same plane and the π-electron cloud is above and below this plane.", "fibs": ["carbonyl"]}
{"text": "The bond angles are approximately 120° as expected of a trigonal coplanar structure (Figure 12.1).", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Fig.12.1 Orbital diagram for the formation of carbonyl group







The carbon-oxygen double bond is polarised due to higher electronegativity of oxygen relative to carbon.", "fibs": ["diagram"]}
{"text": "Hence, the carbonyl carbon is an electrophilic (Lewis acid), and carbonyl oxygen, a nucleophilic (Lewis base) centre.", "fibs": ["carbonyl"]}
{"text": "Carbonyl compounds have substantial dipole moments and are polar than ethers.", "fibs": ["Carbonyl"]}
{"text": "The high polarity of the carbonyl group is explained on the basis of resonance involving a neutral (A) and a dipolar (B) structures as shown.", "fibs": ["polarity"]}
