{"text": "Reduction

(i) Reduction to alcohols: Aldehydes and ketones are reduced to primary and secondary alcohols respectively by sodium borohydride (NaBH4) or lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4) as well as by catalytic hydrogenation (Unit 11, Class XII).", "fibs": ["sodium"]}
{"text": "(ii) Reduction to hydrocarbons: The carbonyl group of aldehydes and ketones is reduced to CH2 group on treatment with zinc-amalgam and concentrated hydrochloric acid [Clemmensen reduction] or with hydrazine followed by heating with sodium or potassium hydroxide in high boiling solvent such as ethylene glycol (Wolff-Kishner reduction).", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Oxidation
Aldehydes differ from ketones in their oxidation reactions.", "fibs": ["Oxidation"]}
{"text": "Aldehydes are easily oxidised to carboxylic acids on treatment with common oxidising agents like nitric acid, potassium permanganate, potassium dichromate, etc.", "fibs": ["carboxylic"]}
{"text": "Even mild oxidising agents, mainly Tollens’ reagent and Fehlings’ reagent also oxidise aldehydes.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Their oxidation involves carbon-carbon bond cleavage to afford a mixture of carboxylic acids having lesser number of carbon atoms than the parent ketone.", "fibs": ["oxidation"]}
{"text": "The mild oxidising agents given below are used to distinguish aldehydes from ketones:
(i) Tollens’ test: On warming an aldehyde with freshly prepared ammoniacal silver nitrate solution (Tollens’ reagent), a bright silver mirror is produced due to the formation of silver metal.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The aldehydes are oxidised to corresponding carboxylate anion.", "fibs": ["anion"]}
{"text": "The reaction occurs in alkaline medium.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "(ii) Fehling’s test: Fehling reagent comprises of two solutions, Fehling solution A and Fehling solution B. Fehling solution A is aqueous copper sulphate and Fehling solution B is alkaline sodium potassium tartarate (Rochelle salt).", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "These two solutions are mixed in equal amounts before test.", "fibs": ["test"]}
{"text": "On heating an aldehyde with Fehling’s reagent, a reddish brown precipitate is obtained.", "fibs": ["heating"]}
{"text": "Aldehydes are oxidised to corresponding carboxylate anion.", "fibs": ["anion"]}
{"text": "Aromatic aldehydes do not respond to this test.", "fibs": ["test"]}
{"text": "(iii) Oxidation of methyl ketones by haloform reaction: Aldehydes and ketones having at least one methyl group linked to the carbonyl carbon atom (methyl ketones) are oxidised by sodium hypohalite to sodium salts of corresponding carboxylic acids having one carbon atom less than that of carbonyl compound.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "The methyl group is converted to haloform.", "fibs": ["methyl"]}
{"text": "This oxidation does not affect a carbon-carbon double bond, if present in the molecule.", "fibs": ["oxidation"]}
