12.8 Physical Properties
Aliphatic carboxylic acids upto nine carbon atoms are colourless liquids at room temperature with unpleasant odours.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "The higher acids are wax like solids and are practically odourless due to their low volatility.", "fibs": ["wax"]}
{"text": "This is due to more extensive association of carboxylic acid molecules through intermolecular hydrogen bonding.", "fibs": ["association"]}
{"text": "The hydrogen bonds are not broken completely even in the vapour phase.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "In fact, most carboxylic acids exist as dimer in the vapour phase or in the aprotic solvents.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "In vapour state or in aprotic solvent


Simple aliphatic carboxylic acids having upto four carbon atoms are miscible in water due to the formation of hydrogen bonds with water.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "The solubility decreases with increasing number of carbon atoms.", "fibs": ["solubility"]}
{"text": "Higher carboxylic acids are practically insoluble in water due to the increased hydrophobic interaction of hydrocarbon part.", "fibs": ["carboxylic"]}
{"text": "Benzoic acid, the simplest aromatic carboxylic acid is nearly insoluble in cold water.", "fibs": ["acid"]}
{"text": "Carboxylic acids are also soluble in less polar organic solvents like benzene, ether, alcohol, chloroform, etc.", "fibs": ["benzene"]}
