{"text": "For convenience, the strength of an acid is generally indicated by its pka value rather than its Ka value.", "fibs": ["convenience"]}
{"text": "pKa = – log Ka
The pKa of hydrochloric acid is –7.0, where as pKa of trifluoroacetic acid (the strongest carboxylic acid), benzoic acid and acetic acid are 0.23, 4.19 and 4.76, respectively.", "fibs": ["pKa"]}
{"text": "Smaller the pKa, the stronger the acid ( the better it is as a proton donor).", "fibs": ["pKa"]}
{"text": "Strong acids have pKa values < 1, the acids with pKa values between 1 and 5 are considered to be moderately strong acids, weak acids have pKa values between 5 and 15, and extremely weak acids have pKa values >15.", "fibs": ["pKa"]}
{"text": "Carboxylic acids are weaker than mineral acids, but they are stronger acids than alcohols and many simple phenols (pKa is ~16 for ethanol and 10 for phenol).", "fibs": ["mineral"]}
{"text": "In fact, carboxylic acids are amongst the most acidic organic compounds you have studied so far.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "You already know why phenols are more acidic than alcohols.", "fibs": ["acidic"]}
{"text": "The higher acidity of carboxylic acids as compared to phenols can be understood similarly.", "fibs": ["acidity"]}
{"text": "The conjugate base of carboxylic acid, a carboxylate ion, is stabilised by two equivalent resonance structures in which the negative charge is at the more electronegative oxygen atom.", "fibs": ["conjugate"]}
{"text": "The conjugate base of phenol, a phenoxide ion, has non-equivalent resonance structures in which the negative charge is at the less electronegative carbon atom.", "fibs": ["conjugate"]}
{"text": "Therefore, resonance in phenoxide ion is not as important as it is in carboxylate ion.", "fibs": ["resonance"]}
{"text": "Further, the negative charge is delocalised over two electronegative oxygen atoms in carboxylate ion whereas it is less effectively delocalised over one oxygen atom and less electronegative carbon atoms in phenoxide ion (Unit 11, Class XII).", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Thus, the carboxylate ion is more stabilised than phenoxide ion, so carboxylic acids are more acidic than phenols.", "fibs": ["ion"]}
{"text": "Effect of substituents on the acidity of carboxylic acids: Substituents may affect the stability of the conjugate base and thus, also affect the acidity of the carboxylic acids.", "fibs": ["Effect"]}
{"text": "Electron withdrawing groups increase the acidity of carboxylic acids by stabilising the conjugate base through delocalisation of the negative charge by inductive and/or resonance effects.", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "Conversely, electron donating groups decrease the acidity by destabilising the conjugate base.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Electron withdrawing group (EWG) stabilises the carboxylate anion and strengthens the acid










Electron donating group (EDG) destabilises the carboxylate anion and weakens the acid






