{"text": "Formation of anhydride
Carboxylic acids on heating with mineral acids such as H2SO4 or with P2O5 give corresponding anhydride.", "fibs": ["anhydride"]}
{"text": "Esterification
Carboxylic acids are esterified with alcohols or phenols in the presence of a mineral acid such as concentrated H2SO4 or HCl gas as a catalyst.", "fibs": ["presence"]}
{"text": "Mechanism of esterification of carboxylic acids: The esterification of carboxylic acids with alcohols is a kind of nucleophilic acyl substitution.", "fibs": ["Mechanism"]}
{"text": "Protonation of the carbonyl oxygen activates the carbonyl group towards nucleophilic addition of the alcohol.", "fibs": ["carbonyl"]}
{"text": "Proton transfer in the tetrahedral intermediate converts the hydroxyl group into –+OH2 group, which, being a better leaving group, is eliminated as neutral water molecule.", "fibs": ["Proton"]}
{"text": "The protonated ester so formed finally loses a proton to give the ester.", "fibs": ["ester"]}
{"text": "Reactions with PCl5, PCl3 and SOCl2
The hydroxyl group of carboxylic acids, behaves like that of alcohols and is easily replaced by chlorine atom on treating with PCl5, PCl3 or SOCl2.", "fibs": ["PCl5"]}
{"text": "Thionyl chloride (SOCl2) is preferred because the other two products are gaseous and escape the reaction mixture making the purification of the products easier.", "fibs": ["chloride"]}
{"text": "Reaction with ammonia
Carboxylic acids react with ammonia to give ammonium salt which on further heating at high temperature give amides.", "fibs": ["Reaction"]}
