{"text": "Reduction
Carboxylic acids are reduced to primary alcohols by lithium aluminium hydride or better with diborane.", "fibs": ["lithium"]}
{"text": "Diborane does not easily reduce functional groups such as ester, nitro, halo, etc.", "fibs": ["ester"]}
{"text": "Sodium borohydride does not reduce the carboxyl group.", "fibs": ["Sodium"]}
{"text": "Decarboxylation
Carboxylic acids lose carbon dioxide to form hydrocarbons when their sodium salts are heated with sodalime (NaOH and CaO in the ratio of 3 : 1).", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "The reaction is known as decarboxylation.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "Alkali metal salts of carboxylic acids also undergo decarboxylation on electrolysis of their aqueous solutions and form hydrocarbons having twice the number of carbon atoms present in the alkyl group of the acid.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "The reaction is known as Kolbe electrolysis (Unit 13, Class XI).", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
